source_code.code:
class RefreshableTableViewer extends TableViewer { 
        public RefreshableTableViewer (final Composite parent, int style) { 
            super(parent, style); 
        } 
        public void refresh () { 
            internalRefresh(null); 
        } 
    }

Bug.WithStack:
(Lynn Kues suggested that I add this PR; see newsgroup thread "Howto get 
ICellModifier to *finish* (not cancel) editing?") 

Scenario: Programmer wants to write code that will allow some gui affordance so 
that when user is editing a cell in a Table, the user can (e.g.) tab to the next 
cell and have a cell editor open immediately (so far all that is needed is for 
the programmer to add a TraverseListener to the CellEditor), AND that tabbing 
action will NOT abandon the changed value of the previously-edited cell.  At the 
moment the programmer can only cause the TraverseListener to cancelEditing() but 
what is wanted is for TableViewer to have a public method, "void 
applyEditorValue()" which simply forwards to tableViewerImpl, like this: 

public void applyEditorValue () { 
    tableViewerImpl.applyEditorValue(); 
} 

The current workaround is for the programmer to do this: 

    /* some access or other */ 
    class RefreshableTableViewer extends TableViewer { 
        public RefreshableTableViewer (final Composite parent, int style) { 
            super(parent, style); 
        } 
        public void refresh () { 
            internalRefresh(null); 
        } 
    }
There are currently no plans to work on this feature

