source_code.code:
public class B {
    void foo() throws FileNotFoundException {
        throw new IOException();
    }
}

Bug.WithStack:
Consider the following case:

public interface A {
    void foo() throws FileNotFoundException;
}
public class B {
    void foo() throws FileNotFoundException {
        throw new IOException();
    }
}

Quick Fix proposes to add a throws clause for IOException, this leads to
a new signature, which is not an overload of the method. The new error is more
severe in that it doesn't offer any Quick Fix.
oops, there's bug:

public class B implements A { ...
By design, Quick fix isn't a refactoring. It doesn't guarantee that the result 
is error free.


I agree, but I still think quick fix should not produce new problems which are 
more severe than the problem it tries to fix. Of course I'm aware, that in 
general, it's not possible to forsee whether a quick fix actually will actually 
reduce problems in quantity or severity.

